Your `submitAsync` method returns a Future that is the result of calling ExecutorService.submit(Runnable).  From [the documentation of that method](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/13/docs/api/java.base/java/util/concurrent/ExecutorService.html#submit%28java.lang.Runnable%29):

&gt;Submits a Runnable task for execution and returns a Future representing that task. The Future&#39;s get method will return null upon *successful* completion.

If you want to return a Future that yields a value, add returns statements to your lambda, so it will be interpreted as a Callable instead of a Runnable:

        return taskToRun.call();
    } catch (Exception e) {
        e.printStackTrace();
        return null;
    }

```
return e1.submit(() -&gt; {
    try {
        if (flag) {
            return;
        }
        taskToRun.call();
    } catch (Exception e) {
        System.out.println(&quot;garbage ---&quot;);
    }
});
```
In this snippet, the lambda passed to `submit` method on `ExecutorService e1` is interpreted as a `Runnable` and that is why the return value is `null`. Check this [documentation][1] for more details. You need to pass the callable `taskToRun` itself to `e1.submit()` to be able to get the return value of the callable. Also, it would be cleaner to put the logic inside the `Callable` itself.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
